<subSubSection id="C323A580FFC31816FF22D0546ACDCE61" lastPageId="57" lastPageNumber="58" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" type="reference_group">
<paragraph id="8B86F60BFFC31817FF22D0546981CBE7" blockId="56.[151,1436,1661,1937]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FF22D0546B2ACAE3" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[151,285,1661,1685]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FF22D0546B2ACAE3" box="[151,285,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FEE2D0546BFBCAE3" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[343,460,1661,1685]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FEE2D0546BFBCAE3" box="[343,460,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FE60D0546812CAE3" bold="true" box="[469,549,1661,1685]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27E9762FFC31817FE60D0546812CAE3" box="[469,549,1661,1685]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are similar enough for earlier authors to regard 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FBE5D0546ED6CAE3" authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1901" box="[1104,1249,1661,1685]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="verrucosa">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FBE5D0546ED6CAE3" box="[1104,1249,1661,1685]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">A. verrucosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a member of 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FF22D0886B9FCACF" box="[151,424,1697,1721]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FF22D0886B2ACACF" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[151,285,1697,1721]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Coronatella</taxonomicName>
rectangula-
</emphasis>
group (e.g., Daday 1910, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA88BFAFFC31817FD7BD088696CCACF" author="Jenkin" box="[718,859,1697,1721]" firstAuthor="Jenkin" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="137 - 160" refId="ref40045" refString="Jenkin, P. M. (1934) Report on the Percy Sladen Expedition to some Rift Valley Lakes in Kenya in 1929. VI. Cladocera from the Rift Valley Lakes in Kenya. Annals and Magazines of Natural History, series 10, 13, 137 - 160 and 281 - 308 (in two parts)." type="journal article" year="1934">Jenkin 1934</bibRefCitation>
; 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FCDDD0886E36CACF" baseAuthorityName="Daday" baseAuthorityYear="1910" box="[872,1025,1697,1721]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rectangula">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FCDDD0886E36CACF" box="[872,1025,1697,1721]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">A. rectangula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
-group). Also the presence of tubercles in both, has lead to confusion (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA88BFAFFC31817FDDDD0EC6920CAAB" author="Johnson" box="[616,791,1733,1757]" firstAuthor="Johnson" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="200 - 205" refId="ref40148" refString="Johnson, D. S. (1956 b) Proposed use of the plenary powers to validate the specific name &quot; verrucosa &quot; Sars, 1901, as published in the combination (Alona verrucosa) (Class Crustacea, Order Cladocera). Bulletin of Zoological Nomenclature, 12 (7 / 8), 200 - 205." type="journal article" year="1956" yearSuffix="b">Johnson 1956b</bibRefCitation>
). Important similarities include (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA88BFAFFC31817FB3FD0EC6AD5CB77" author="Van Damme &amp; Dumont" firstAuthor="Van Damme" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 44" refId="ref41120" refString="Van Damme, K. &amp; Dumont, H. J. (2008 b) Further division of Alona Baird, 1843: separation and position of Coronatella Dybowski &amp; Grochowski and Ovalona gen. n. (Crustacea: Cladocera). Zootaxa, 1960, 1 - 44." type="journal article" year="2008" yearSuffix="b">
<collectingRegion id="49FD38E9FFC31817FB3FD0EC6E80CAAB" box="[1162,1207,1733,1757]" country="Turkey" name="Van" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Van</collectingRegion>
Damme &amp; Dumont 2008b
</bibRefCitation>
): 1) five pairs of limbs with reductions, typical for the 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FCF1D0C069E4CB77" box="[836,979,1769,1793]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Coronatella-</emphasis>
branch (IDL with two setae, reduction of anterior setae in P1, exIII with six setae, no gnV); 2) specialized setal armature (IDL on P1); 3) The 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FB46D1246FACCB53" authorityName="Sars" authorityYear="1901" box="[1267,1435,1805,1829]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="monacantha">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FB46D1246FACCB53" box="[1267,1435,1805,1829]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">A. monacantha</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group (to be removed from 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FE60D118682FCB3F" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[469,536,1841,1865]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FE60D118682FCB3F" box="[469,536,1841,1865]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Alona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) has all characters of 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FCA2D11869AACB3F" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[791,925,1841,1865]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FCA2D11869AACB3F" box="[791,925,1841,1865]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but some peculiarities of 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FB7AD1186F74CB3F" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[1231,1347,1841,1865]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FB7AD1186F74CB3F" box="[1231,1347,1841,1865]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(strong armature IDL on P1, denticle on labrum) as well, hence seems intermediate; 4) In general dimensions of body and postabdomen, 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FE8FD1506BF7CBE7" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[314,448,1913,1937]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FE8FD1506BF7CBE7" box="[314,448,1913,1937]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC31817FE42D150685BCBE7" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[503,620,1913,1937]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FE42D150685BCBE7" box="[503,620,1913,1937]" italics="true" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC31817FDC6D15068F7CBE7" bold="true" box="[627,704,1913,1937]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27E9762FFC31817FDC6D15068F7CBE7" box="[627,704,1913,1937]" pageId="56" pageNumber="57" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
look nearly identical.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B86F60BFFC21816FF70D6B16ACDCE61" blockId="57.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF70D6B16B7CCCC6" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[197,331,152,176]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF70D6B16B7CCCC6" box="[197,331,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE34D6B16BC2CCC6" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[385,501,152,176]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE34D6B16BC2CCC6" box="[385,501,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seem both natural assemblages with a separate evolution. The head pore configuration is distinct and stable in each genus (two + cosmaria in 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FCF4D6956982CCA2" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[833,949,188,212]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FCF4D6956982CCA2" box="[833,949,188,212]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
versus three + no lateral pores in 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FA8BD6956AFECC8E" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FA8BD6956AFECC8E" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The phylogenetic importance of head pores in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FCE5D6F66980CC81" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski, 1894 emend. Frey" authorityYear="1967" box="[848,951,223,247]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aloninae">Aloninae</taxonomicName>
may be overrated, but the difference is significant in that the typical head pore 
<typeStatus id="548248A9FFC21816FDE0D72D68B2CD6A" box="[597,645,260,284]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
arose only once in an ancestral 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC5AD72D6E53CD6A" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[1007,1124,260,284]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC5AD72D6E53CD6A" box="[1007,1124,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, maybe even from the 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FAD2D72C6AD2CD36" authorityName="Dumont &amp; Silva-Briano" authorityYear="2000" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Karualona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FAD2D72C6AD2CD36" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Karualona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="548248A9FFC21816FF58D7016B17CD36" box="[237,288,296,320]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">type</typeStatus>
. It gave rise to a subtle diversity of head pore arrangements in 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC42D7016E5CCD36" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[1015,1131,296,320]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC42D7016E5CCD36" box="[1015,1131,296,320]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The same can be said for postabdomen armature (lateral spines thicker and basal spine shorter in 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC7AD7656E73CD12" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[975,1092,332,356]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC7AD7656E73CD12" box="[975,1092,332,356]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and other specific characters (
<figureCitation id="1302EA8EFFC21816FF2AD7466AC4CDF1" box="[159,243,367,391]" captionStart="FIGURE 29" captionStartId="55.[151,250,951,974]" captionTargetBox="[178,1431,199,918]" captionTargetId="figure-523@55.[151,1436,195,929]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 29. Phylogenetic relationships and evolution in Anthalona gen. n. Parsimony analysis based on 14 morphological characters with Karualona as outgroup. The trees illustrate the hypothesis of a basal position of A. simplex n. sp. and A. brandorffi in Anthalona gen. n. Evolution of four characters plotted next to the tree. A. 50% Majority-rule consensus tree of 4598 trees with bootstrap values at nodes. The separate position of A. simplex n. sp. has high support. B. Strict consensus tree from six most parsimonious trees obtained by heuristic search, with values plotted from the 50% majority rule tree of these six (tree itself not shown). Evolution in the genus shows an increase of specialization/complexity of four synapomorphies, illustrated at the right (pores, IDL armature, sixth scraper of P2 and labral keel). The most primitive condition is found in A. simplex n. sp. Head pores in the genus show an increase of complexity in the lateral cosmaria (from simple unconstricted to involuted and constricted). Limb modifications for scraping, increase in specialization, from fine and similar setules in the basal taxa to strongly modified spines towards the crown taxa. Finally, denticles on the labral keel are absent in A. simplex n. sp. and A. brandorffi and appear in the genus together with stronger specialized scraping mechanisms. Their basal position within the genus is therefore confirmed by more than one character." pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
). In the antennae of 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE61D759686DCDFE" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[468,602,368,392]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE61D759686DCDFE" box="[468,602,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FD3AD7596934CDFE" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[655,771,368,392]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FD3AD7596934CDFE" box="[655,771,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, strong changes and specialisations have occurred independently, suggesting important plasticity in these traits (e.g., 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC9DD7BD69AACDDA" baseAuthorityName="Green" baseAuthorityYear="1952" box="[808,925,404,428]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="holdeni">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC9DD7BD69AACDDA" box="[808,925,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">C. holdeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC61D7BD6E06CDDA" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[980,1073,404,428]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="acuta">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC61D7BD6E06CDDA" box="[980,1073,404,428]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">A. acuta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The limb characters shared by both 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF65D7916B61CDA6" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[208,342,440,464]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF65D7916B61CDA6" box="[208,342,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE3BD7916835CDA6" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[398,514,440,464]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE3BD7916835CDA6" box="[398,514,440,464]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FDBFD791686ECDA6" bold="true" box="[522,601,440,464]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27E9762FFC21816FDBFD791686ECDA6" box="[522,601,440,464]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are mainly reductions. As a general trend in the evolution of these microcrustaceans (reduction of setae), such reductions may either have arisen independently or stem from a common ancestor.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C323A580FFC21816FF70D40D6B34C82E" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B86F60BFFC21816FF70D40D6EBFCF2A" blockId="57.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
Similarity in morphological form may be a result of a reversal, close common ancestry, parallel evolution or convergence. Homoplasy may occur under similar adaptive pressures or by evolutionary constraints (constraints to structural solutions; e.g., 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA88BFAFFC21816FE0ED4456877CEF2" author="Wake" box="[443,576,620,644]" firstAuthor="Wake" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" pagination="543 - 567" refId="ref41279" refString="Wake, D. B. (1991) Homoplasy: the result of natural selection, or evidence of design limitations? The American Naturalist, 138, 543 - 567." type="journal article" year="1991">
<collectingCountry id="F32EB69BFFC21816FE0ED4456BCDCEF2" box="[443,506,620,644]" name="Wake Island" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Wake</collectingCountry>
1991
</bibRefCitation>
). The similarities in body size and postabdomen between 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FB56D4456F5ECEF2" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[1251,1385,620,644]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FB56D4456F5ECEF2" box="[1251,1385,620,644]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF22D4B96B3BCEDE" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[151,268,656,680]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF22D4B96B3BCEDE" box="[151,268,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may result from such constraints, although details on their feeding and ecology are yet to be investigated. Reductions on limbs in 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE4DD49D6849CEBA" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[504,638,692,716]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE4DD49D6849CEBA" box="[504,638,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FD0FD49D6918CEBA" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[698,815,692,716]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FD0FD49D6918CEBA" box="[698,815,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
may also be correlated with miniaturization; both are among the smaller 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FED9D4FE6BE4CE99" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski, 1894 emend. Frey" authorityYear="1967" box="[364,467,727,751]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aloninae">Aloninae</taxonomicName>
genera. In the 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FDCFD4F1692BCE86" box="[634,796,728,752]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FDCFD4F1688ACE86" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[634,701,728,752]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alona</taxonomicName>
guttata-
</emphasis>
group for example, which belongs to an entirely different lineage (of six-limbed 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE20D4D56BEFCF62" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[405,472,764,788]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE20D4D56BEFCF62" box="[405,472,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Alona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), reductions seem correlated with a decrease in body size. In any case, 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FB4DD4D56F5ACF62" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[1272,1389,764,788]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FB4DD4D56F5ACF62" box="[1272,1389,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF22D5096B2ACF4E" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[151,285,800,824]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF22D5096B2ACF4E" box="[151,285,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are examples of the typical general small, successful 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FCCED5096989CF4E" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[891,958,800,824]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FCCED5096989CF4E" box="[891,958,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Alona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
body shape. However, closer examination shows that comparative body shapes of 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FDE0D56D6915CF2A" box="[597,802,836,860]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FDE0D56D68FECF2A" box="[597,713,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
are not so similar (
<figureCitation id="1302EA8EFFC21816FC4CD56D6E4BCF2A" box="[1017,1148,836,860]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 27" captionStart-1="FIGURE 28" captionStartId-0="52.[151,250,1827,1850]" captionStartId-1="53.[151,250,1548,1571]" captionTargetBox-0="[169,1416,565,1806]" captionTargetBox-1="[161,1419,204,1525]" captionTargetId-0="figure-517@52.[151,1436,532,1817]" captionTargetId-1="figure-117@53.[151,1436,195,1527]" captionTargetPageId-0="52" captionTargetPageId-1="53" captionText-0="FIGURE 27. Neotropical species of Anthalona gen. n. A. Anthalona verrucosa verrucosa (Sars, 1901), Lençóis Maranhenses, NE–Brazil, from culture (without tubercles on valves), Leg. K. Van Damme. B. Anthalona verrucosa verrucosa (Sars, 1901), Lençóis Maranhenses, NE-Brazil, from sample, same population as in A but with tubercles on valves, Leg. K. Van Damme. C. Anthalona verrucosa ssp. (Sars, 1901) from Fra Bartelomeo de las Casas, Guatemala, Leg. H.J. Dumont. D. Anthalona verru-" captionText-1="FIGURE 28. Asian and African species of Anthalona gen. n., compared to Anthalona verrucosa (Sars, 1901). A. Anthalona verrucosa verrucosa (Sars, 1901), Lençóis Maranhenses, NE-Brazil, from culture, Leg. K. Van Damme. B. Anthalona obtusa n. sp., Borneo, Palangka Raya University Campus, Leg. H.J. Dumont. C. Anthalona harti harti n. ssp., Maun, Okavango Delta, Botswana, Leg. H.J. Dumont. D. Anthalona harti occidentalis n. ssp., Lake Télé, Mali, Leg. H.J. Dumont. E. Anthalona simplex n. sp. from Katanga, DR Congo, Leg. K. Martens. F. Anthalona mediterranea from Wadi Shawqah, Sharjah, UAE, raised from culture, Leg. K. Van Damme." pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Figs 27–28</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B86F60BFFC21816FF70D5416B34C82E" blockId="57.[151,1436,151,1112]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF70D5416B7CCFF6" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[197,331,872,896]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF70D5416B7CCFF6" box="[197,331,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FE31D5416BCFCFF6" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[388,504,872,896]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. n.">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FE31D5416BCFCFF6" box="[388,504,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FDB5D5416878CFF6" bold="true" box="[512,591,872,896]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27E9762FFC21816FDB5D5416878CFF6" box="[512,591,872,896]" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" rank="genus">gen. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
do not necessarily share a close common ancestor. Evolutionary pressures under similar conditions and/or constraints in the 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FD76D5A5691ECFD2" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski, 1894 emend. Frey" authorityYear="1967" box="[707,809,908,932]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Aloninae">Aloninae</taxonomicName>
“Bauplan” may have lead to homoplasy in external and internal characters, with body shape, postabdomen, even limbs, similar. It results in a small model, successful in littoral environments. An independent test to see whether 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FCB2D5FD69BACF9A" authorityName="Dybowski &amp; Grochowski" authorityYear="1894" box="[775,909,980,1004]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Coronatella" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FCB2D5FD69BACF9A" box="[775,909,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Coronatella</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FC71D5FD6E0ECF9A" authorityName="Van Damme, Sinev &amp; Dumont" authorityYear="2011" box="[964,1081,980,1004]" class="Branchiopoda" family="Chydoridae" genus="Anthalona" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FC71D5FD6E0ECF9A" box="[964,1081,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Anthalona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share a close common ancestor is by molecular analysis (
<collectingRegion id="49FD38E9FFC21816FE77D5DE6BC7C879" box="[450,496,1015,1039]" country="Turkey" name="Van" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Van</collectingRegion>
Damme &amp; Dumont, 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FD59D5D1690EC866" box="[748,825,1016,1040]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">unpubl</emphasis>
.), not included in this study. It is this general small “ 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FF16D2356AC1C842" box="[163,246,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">
<taxonomicName id="4C398D88FFC21816FF16D2356AD9C842" authorityName="Baird" authorityYear="1843" box="[163,238,1052,1076]" class="Branchiopoda" genus="Alona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diplostraca" pageId="57" pageNumber="58" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alona</taxonomicName>
”
</emphasis>
body shape that caused many of our historical taxonomical problems in the lump genus (
<collectingRegion id="49FD38E9FFC21816FB44D2356F29C842" box="[1265,1310,1052,1076]" country="Turkey" name="Van" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">Van</collectingRegion>
Damme 
<emphasis id="B94D2A19FFC21816FA3DD2346A83C82E" italics="true" pageId="57" pageNumber="58">et al.</emphasis>
, 2010)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
